abstract: SYRACUSE, N.Y., Oct. 10.--Five members of the Salvation Army, four of them women, were sent to the penitentiary to-night. The Salvationists were arrested for violating a city ordinance by singing and playingug upon tambourines on the streets. They demanded a jury trial and were convicted and sent to the penitentiary for 15 days. To-night five more Salvationists were arrested and locked up for the same offense. They will be tried to-morrow.

abstract: PARIS, Oct. 13.--Gen. de l'Isle telegraphs that the wound in the leg which Gen. Negrier received in the engagement at Kep is so painful that it is necessary that that officer should take rest, and that he would therefore join the column. He was traveling under the name of Richardson, as a book agent. He will be taken to Kansas as soon as the proper papers arrive. He is charged with forging $19,000 worth of school bonds in December, 1874. He was arrested at Topeka, but escaped the following July and went to South America."

abstract: MOBILE, Oct. 26.--On this the ninetieth day of the drought, a general rain, extending as far north as Tennessee, and perhaps further, has passed over the Country, and rain is now falling steadily here. Fall planting of small crops will now be pushed vigorously.

abstract: SAN FRANCISCO, Oct. 29.--The following particulars of the storms on the coast of Lower California were learned this morning. abstract: HALIFAX, Nova Scotia, Oct. 30.--The students at King's College, at Windsor, have rebelled, and demanded the dismissal of President Dart and Profs. Do Formentin and Butler. The college lectures have been suspended, and the students are idling about the town.

abstract: WEST CHESTER, Penn., Oct. 30.--In the Court of Quarter Sessions this afternoon George M. Rupert, Secretary and Treasurer of the Borough of West Chester and Treasurer of the Pennsylvania Mutual Fire Insurance Company of Chester County, entered a plea of guilty to the charge of having embezzled funds amounting to about $27,000 belonging to the above-named corporations. Sentence was deferred until Thursday next, and Rupert was remanded to jail.

abstract: The business men's Cleveland and Hendricks parade to-morrow promises to be so large that it is to be divided into two divisions. Gen. J. B. Woodward will command one and E.D. abstract: Rain and mud did not dampen the ardor of the Brooklyn independent Republicans last night, when their campaign committee of 100 held a mass meeting in the Brooklyn Rink. abstract: DETROIT, Mich., Oct. 30.--Ex-Gov. Moses, of South Carolina, who is under arrest, charged with swindling the Rev. Dr. Rexford, the Rev. Mr. Atterbury, and others, attempted suicide this morning by hanging himself in his cell. Mr. Moses was brought into the Police Court this afternoon and charged with swindling. He pleaded guilty, and was sentenced to three months in the House of Correction. His lawyer hopes to effect his transfer to an insane asylum.

abstract: NO. 124 HICKS-STREET, BROOKLYN, N.Y. I am told that Stewart L. Woodford is  stating that I wrote a letter to Mr. Garfield urging Mr. Blaine's appointment and indorsing his personal character. Mr. Woodford has been misinformed. abstract: COLUMBUS, Ohio, Oct. 30.--At a meeting of the stockholders of the Columbus Baseball Club this evening the proposition of the Pittsburg Club to pay $6,000 for the transfer of players was accepted. This action was taken owing to the small chance for Columbus to remain in the American Association next year, since the disbandment of the Toledo Club.

abstract: HAVANA, Oct. 25.--It is said in official circles that Gen. abstract: NEW-BLOOMFIELD, Penn., Oct. 30.--The boiler of a steam thrasher on the farm of Daniel Wentz, of Jackson Township, Perry County, exploded this afternoon killing a young man named David Snyder. The barn was fired and consumed together with 3,400 bushels of grain and many farming implements. The building and its contents were insured for $1,700.
